1154–1196","1156–Male":"1156–Overleden","1160–Male":"1160–Overleden","1103–1162":"1103–van8januari1162to7januari1163","1149":"1149","1103":"1103","1156":"1156","1122":"1122","1154":"1154","1196":"1196","1162":"van 8 januari 1162 to 7 januari 1163","about 1122":"circa 1122","1160":"1160","Kenilworth Castle, Warwickshire, England":"Kenilworth, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Coleshill, Warwickshire, England":"Coleshill, Warwickshire, England"},"en":{"about 1122–1162":"about 1122–from 8 January 1162 to 7 January 1163","1122–1162":"1122–from8January1162to7January1163","1149–Male":"1149–Deceased","1154–1196":"1154–1196","1156–Male":"1156–Deceased","1160–Male":"1160–Deceased","1103–1162":"1103–from8January1162to7January1163","1149":"1149","1103":"1103","1156":"1156","1122":"1122","1154":"1154","1196":"1196","1162":"from 8 January 1162 to 7 January 1163","about 1122":"about 1122","1160":"1160","Kenilworth Castle, Warwickshire, England":"Kenilworth, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Coleshill, Warwickshire, England":"Coleshill, Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clinton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Louth, Westmeath) and Scottish: shortened form of   McClinton  .","English: habitational name, either from Glympton in Oxfordshire, named as ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) on the Glym river’, a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright stream’, or from Glinton in Northamptonshire, early recorded as <i>Clinton</i> (named with an unrecorded Old English element akin to Middle Low German <i>glinde</i> ‘enclosure, fence’ + Old English <i>tūn</i>). The surname was taken to Ireland in or before the 16th century.","History: Charles Clinton (born 1690 in Longford, Ireland) organized a group of colonists and founded the settlement of Little Britain, Ulster County, NY, in 1731. His son George Clinton (1739–1812) was governor of NY (1777–95), and they had many prominent descendants. — An English aristocratic family called <i>Clinton</i> was founded by Geoffrey de Clinton (flourished 1130), who held lands at Glympton, Oxfordshire. He was chamberlain and treasurer to Henry I (1100–35)."],"variants":[{"name":"McClinton","meanings":["Irish (northern) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Fhionntain</b> (Scottish), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntáin</b> (Irish) ‘son of the servant (i.e. devotee) of (Saint) <i>Fionntan</i>’, whose name has been explained as ‘the white ancient’."]}]},{"name":"Osbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It is not now common, but in the earlier 20th century it enjoyed a modest vogue in Britain, being borne for example by the cartoonist  Osbert Lancaster  (  1908–86 ) and the writer  Osbert Sitwell  (  1892–1969 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Osbert Clinton was born about 1122, in Kenilworth, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Osbert de Clinton I. He had at least 4 sons. He died from 8 January 1162 to 7 January 1163, in Coleshill, Warwickshire, England."},"et":{"about 1122–1162":"umbes 1122–8. jaanuar 1162 kuni 7. jaanuar 1163","1122–1162":"1122–8.jaanuar1162kuni7.jaanuar1163","1149–Male":"1149–Surnud","1154–1196":"1154–1196","1156–Male":"1156–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1103–1162":"1103–8.jaanuar1162kuni7.jaanuar1163","1149":"1149","1103":"1103","1156":"1156","1122":"1122","1154":"1154","1196":"1196","1162":"8. jaanuar 1162 kuni 7. jaanuar 1163","about 1122":"umbes 1122","1160":"1160","Kenilworth Castle, Warwickshire, England":"Kenilworth, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Coleshill, Warwickshire, England":"Coleshill, Warwickshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1122–1162":"noin 1122–vuodesta 8. tammikuuta 1162 vuoteen 7. tammikuuta 1163","1122–1162":"1122–vuodesta8.tammikuuta1162vuoteen7.tammikuuta1